%[text] # Design UPS Control for Data Center
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%[text] ## Overview
%[text] This example shows how to model and validate a double-conversion uninterruptible power supply control for a data center electrical system. The key requirement is uninterrupted, conditioned power to mission-critical loads during grid disturbances and equipment events.
%[text] Data centers differ from many industrial loads in three ways :
%[text] - Fast, correlated load steps can occur over milliseconds in large compute clusters.
%[text] - Continuity requirements are strict. Even short interruptions can terminate workloads.
%[text] - Capacity scales in modular blocks, often deployed with N+1 redundancy. \
%[text] ## Double-Conversion UPS
%[text] The double-conversion UPS is so named because power is converted twice: from AC to DC by the rectifier, and from DC back to AC by the inverter. This double conversion is what enables the zero-transfer-time guarantee and the load is always powered by the inverter, which is  powered by the DC bus, which is simultaneously maintained by the rectifier and the battery. During a grid failure, the rectifier ceases operation, and the battery sustains the DC bus voltage. As a result, the transition is seamless and the inverter operation remains unaffected.
%[text] ![](text:image:30e4)
%[text] The main power path in a double-conversion UPS is:
%[text] - Grid (480 V AC, 60 Hz) feeds the Active Front End (AFE) rectifier
%[text] - Rectifier regulates the DC bus to 800 V, drawing sinusoidal current from the grid at unity power factor
%[text] - Battery floats on the DC bus, automatically supplying or absorbing the difference between AFE output and load demand
%[text] - Output inverter converts 800 V DC to 480 V AC and supplies the IT load with tightly regulated voltage and frequency
%[text] - Load (IT equipment, aggregated as variable resistor) is permanently connected to the inverter output \
%[text] The DC bus is the critical intermediate node. Its voltage level determines the quality of the AC output the inverter can produce, and its regulation during grid disturbances determines whether the UPS meets its VFI-SS-111 classification.
%[text] #### **IEC 62040-3:2011 — Classification VFI-SS-111**
%[text] The UPS in this example is designed to meet IEC 62040-3 classification VFI-SS-111 \[5\], which defines performance requirements for voltage regulation, frequency control, and dynamic response.  VFI systems correspond to online double-conversion operation, where the inverter continuously supplies the load and isolates it from input disturbances. 
%[text] - No transfer during grid loss
%[text] - Load voltage decoupled from grid disturbances \
%[text] This behavior is demonstrated in:
%[text] - Case 1 for steady-state operation
%[text] - Case 2 during LVRT events
%[text] - Case 4 during complete loss of mains \
%[text] The SS classification defines steady-state output performance, requiring tight voltage regulation and a near-sinusoidal waveform. In this model, the inverter regulates the 480 V output while the DC bus ensures stable operation. As a result:
%[text] - Load voltage remains within acceptable limits
%[text] - Power quality is maintained across operating conditions \
%[text] This is validated in:
%[text] - Case 1 under nominal conditions
%[text] - Case 5 during parallel operation of UPS units \
%[text] The 111 classification represents dynamic performance under transient conditions, including voltage deviation and recovery. The UPS limits voltage excursions and quickly restores steady-state operation, which is critical for sensitive IT loads. In this model:
%[text] - The DC bus remains regulated during disturbances
%[text] - Battery support enables seamless ride-through \
%[text] This is evaluated in:
%[text] - Case 2 during voltage sag response
%[text] - Case 3 during battery ride-through
%[text] - Case 4 during sudden loss of mains
%[text] - Case 5 during UPS unit outage and load redistribution \
%[text] ## Model Architecture
%[text] #### Model Overview
%[text] The model represents a modular data center UPS system with an 800 V DC internal bus and a 480 V AC external interface. It includes three UPS modules rated at 5 MW each to enable parallel operation and N+1 redundancy. The load and scenarios in this example use two configurations:
%[text] - Cases 1 through 4 use a single UPS module to focus on control behavior during operating and disturbance conditions.
%[text] - Case 5 enables all three UPS modules to demonstrate parallel operation and N+1 redundancy. \
%[text]  ![](text:image:03b2)
%[text] 
%[text] Power is continuously processed through the rectifier, DC link, and inverter. The inverter always supplies the load. The rectifier and battery together regulate the DC bus under all operating conditions.
%[text] The model also includes a backup generator for extended loss of the utility supply. The battery provides immediate support during grid loss. The generator ramps up and supplies the system for longer-duration events.
%[text] For more information, see the  [`Model Architecture`](file:./UPSControlDesign\ModelArchitecture.m) of this example.
%%
%[text] ## Simulation Scenarios
%[text] You can create the data center load model using [DataCenterLoadModel](file:.\UPSControlDesign\DataCenterLoadModel.m). For more information on creating plant models for data centers please refer to [CreateDataCenter](file:..\CreatePlantModels\CreateDataCenterModel.m)
%[text] This plot gives the server utilization for all the scenarios. For Cases 1–4, the server utilization is set to 45% of the peak profile since only a single UPS unit is used to demonstrate these operating conditions. For Case 5, all three UPS units are enabled and the server utilization is set to 100% of the peak profile to demonstrate parallel operation and N+1 redundancy.
plot.serverUtilization; %[output:22c69fbb]
%%
%[text] ### Case 1 : Normal Operation
%[text] This scenario represents steady-state operation with nominal utility voltage at 480 V and 60 Hz. The UPS regulates the DC bus and supplies the IT load through the inverter. You can modify the parameters of the model in [DataCenterParam](file:.\UPSControlDesign\DataCenterParam.m). Initialize the parameters for case 1 and run the model.
if ~bdIsLoaded('UPSControl'), load_system('UPSControl'); end
timeRange = [6 8];
simoutData = sim('UPSControl','SrcWorkspace','current');
%[text] **Scenario description** :
%[text] The system operates under nominal grid conditions at rated voltage and frequency, supplying the IT load through the inverter.
%[text] **Purpose** :
%[text] Verify steady-state control performance of the rectifier, DC bus, and inverter.
%[text] **What to look for :**
%[text] Stable power flow, regulated load voltage, and minimal battery current with DC bus voltage held near its reference.
%[text] This plot shows the active power of  grid, UPS, and load. Stable active power indicates a stable control.
plot.powerFlow(simoutData.logsout,timeRange); %[output:229657eb]
%[text] This plot shows the load voltage and current. 
plot.loadVI(simoutData.logsout,timeRange); %[output:8f749816]
%[text] This plot shows the DC bus voltage and BESS current. 
plot.dcBusVI(simoutData.logsout,timeRange,timeRange); %[output:15a4566d]
%%
%[text] ### Case 2 : Low-Voltage Ride Though (LVRT) Support
%[text] **Scenario Description :**
%[text] You can use this scenario to assess how the data center electrical system responds to severe and moderate voltage disturbances while maintaining uninterrupted supply to critical loads.  You can choose any of the LVRT profiles from the available grid operators through gridCode selection. These profiles are representative of typical grid code requirements and are implemented based on reference \[1\]. For a detailed analysis on the LVRT support refer to [UPSLVRTSupport](file:.\UPSControlDesign\UPSLVRTSupport.m)
%[text] **Purpose** : Verify that the UPS maintains uninterrupted load supply during voltage sags that follow representative grid code LVRT profiles. You can also use the ITIC curve to evaluate whether the load voltage remains within acceptable operating limits during these voltage disturbances. Compliance with this curve ensures that the critical IT load continues to function reliably without triggering faults or shutdowns.
%[text] **What to look for** : Load voltage stays regulated while grid voltage dips, the DC bus remains within limits, and the ITIC assessment remains within acceptable regions for the disturbance duration \[4\].
%[text] This plot gives the LVRT profiles for different grid codes.
plot.lvrtProfiles; %[output:985a9ead]
lvrtProfileName = "AESO"; %[control:dropdown:2ced]{"position":[19,25]}
if ~bdIsLoaded('UPSControl'), load_system('UPSControl'); end
LVRT;
timeRange = [2.9 10];
simoutData = sim('UPSControl','SrcWorkspace','current');
%[text]  This plot shows the active power of  grid, UPS, and load. Stable active power indicates a stable control.
plot.powerFlow(simoutData.logsout,timeRange); %[output:15d602e9]
%[text] This plot shows the load voltage and current. Load voltage and current are stable through out the operation
plot.loadVI(simoutData.logsout,timeRange); %[output:16d3cf18]
%[text] This plot shows the DC bus voltage and BESS current. 
plot.dcBusVI(simoutData.logsout,timeRange,timeRange); %[output:9a8b5b0f]
%[text] This plot shows the load voltage, and the ITIC/CBEMA assessment curves
plot.lvrtAssessment(simoutData.logsout, 1, 'AESO', [2.9 10]); %[output:06d91e3c]
%%
%[text] ### Case 3 : Battery Ride Through
%[text] **Scenario description :** 
%[text] Grid voltage steps to 0.5 pu at 5 s and returns to 1 pu at 5.5 s. During the sag, the battery sustains the DC bus so the inverter continues supplying the load.
%[text] **Purpose :** 
%[text] Verify seamless transition to battery support during a structured sag and recovery back to rectifier support when grid voltage returns.
%[text] **What to look for** :
%[text] Battery current increases during the sag, DC bus voltage remains regulated, and load voltage does not exhibit any interruption during the transition.
if ~bdIsLoaded('UPSControl'), load_system('UPSControl'); end
BESSRideThrough;
simoutData = sim('UPSControl','SrcWorkspace','current');
timeRange = [2.9 4];
%[text]  This plot shows the active power of  grid, UPS, and load. Stable active power indicates a stable control.
plot.powerFlow(simoutData.logsout,timeRange); %[output:71a09597]
%[text] This plot shows the load voltage and current. Load voltage and current are stable through out the operation
plot.loadVI(simoutData.logsout,timeRange); %[output:3d30891e]
%[text] This plot shows the DC bus voltage and BESS current. 
plot.dcBusVI(simoutData.logsout,timeRange,timeRange); %[output:5d8289c0]
%%
%[text] ### Case 4 : Sudden Loss of Mains
%[text] **Scenario description :** 
%[text] The utility supply is completely lost instantaneously, representing a full grid outage condition.
%[text] **Purpose :** 
%[text] Verify that the inverter continues supplying the load without interruption and evaluate the transition to battery and generator support.
%[text] **What to look for :** 
%[text] Grid power drops to zero, battery immediately supplies power, DC bus stays within limits, and load voltage remains uninterrupted.
if ~bdIsLoaded('UPSControl'), load_system('UPSControl'); end
MainsLoss;
timeRange = [3.8 5.5];
simoutData = sim('UPSControl','SrcWorkspace','current');
%[text]  This plot shows the active power of  grid, UPS, and load. Stable active power indicates a stable control.
plot.powerFlow(simoutData.logsout,timeRange); %[output:09ec8dc8]
%[text] This plot shows the load voltage and current. 
plot.loadVI(simoutData.logsout,timeRange); %[output:5a2b9f7f]
%[text] This plot shows the DC bus voltage and BESS current. 
plot.dcBusVI(simoutData.logsout,timeRange,timeRange); %[output:2993e4b5]
%%
%[text] ### Case 5 : N+1 Redundancy Analysis
%[text] **Scenario description** :
%[text] Three UPS modules operate in parallel. One module trips offline during operation while the remaining modules continue supplying the load. At 5s, UPS3 goes offline suddenly and the remaining UPS units pick up the load instantaneously
%[text] **Purpose** : 
%[text] Demonstrate load sharing and validate N+1 redundancy capability.
%[text] **What to look for** :
%[text] Total load power remains continuous, remaining UPS units increase output to share load, and load voltage remains stable without disturbance.
if ~bdIsLoaded('UPSControl'), load_system('UPSControl'); end
RedundancyAnalysis;
timeRange = [5 5.5];
simoutData = sim('UPSControl','SrcWorkspace','current');
%[text]  This plot shows the active power of  grid, UPS, and load. Stable active power indicates a stable control.
plot.powerFlow(simoutData.logsout,timeRange); %[output:64201d60]
%[text] This plot shows the load voltage and current.
plot.loadVI(simoutData.logsout,timeRange); %[output:75f1fc70]
%[text] This plot shows the power output of all the UPS units. 
plot.powerFlowUPS(simoutData.logsout,timeRange); %[output:2831fe5d]
%[text] This plot shows the DC bus voltage and BESS current. 
plot.dcBusVI(simoutData.logsout,timeRange,timeRange); %[output:5a81b0eb]
%[text] ## References
%[text] 1\. Open Compute Project Data Center Facility Power Distribution Sub-Project, Low Voltage DC (LVDC) Power Distribution White Paper v1.0, March 2026.
%[text] 2\*\*.\*\*  S. Shah, V. Gevorgian, P. Koralewicz, R. Wallen, B. Mather, B. Kroposki, and J. Kurtz, *Data Center Power Systems: Architectures, Impact on Grid Reliability, Modeling Considerations, and Megawatt-Scale Hardware Testing*, NLR/PR-5D00-96746, National Laboratory of the Rockies, Golden CO, March 2026
%[text] 3\. C. Ross and J. Follum, *Electromagnetic Transient Modeling of Large Data Centers for Grid-Level Studies*, PNNL-38817, Pacific Northwest National Laboratory, Richland WA, December 2025.
%[text] 4\. Voltage Disturbance, *ITIC Curve – Voltage Disturbance*, Available online: https://voltage-disturbance.com/voltage-quality/itic-curve/, accessed 2026.
%[text] 5\. Siemens AG, "Modeling of Uninterruptible Power Supply Systems for Data Centers," Totally Integrated Power Technical Series, 2020. \[Online\]. Available: https://assets.new.siemens.com/siemens/assets/api/uuid:b5faad38e4934b6c444ee34704af0114290ee811/03-modelling-ups-in-simaris-design.pdf. \[Accessed: 2026\].
